    {
      "id": "8065dfd5_73af72a5",
      "file_path": "certServiceClient/src/test/java/org/onap/oom/certservice/client/configuration/validation/UriValidatorTest.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 35,
      "message": "Should these be valid URIs? Doesn't seem useful for certs.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6044,
        "name": "Remigiusz Janeczek",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "remigiusz.janeczek@nokia.com",
        "username": "rjanecze"
      },
      "updated": "2020-11-18 08:03:01.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "51f0c261_c129a278",
      "file_path": "certServiceClient/src/test/java/org/onap/oom/certservice/client/configuration/validation/UriValidatorTest.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 35,
      "message": "According to RFC 3986 section 3.2 (https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986#section-3.2) Authority is optional. And section 3.3 Path could be empty or begin with \"/\". It couldn't useful in cert, but must be allowed. See RFC 5820 (https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-4.2.1.6), in this we can read: \" \n   When the subjectAltName extension contains a URI, the name MUST be\n   stored in the uniformResourceIdentifier (an IA5String).  The name\n   MUST NOT be a relative URI, and it MUST follow the URI syntax and\n   encoding rules specified in [RFC3986].\"",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6310,
        "name": "Tomasz Wr�bel",
        "display_name": "Tomasz Wrobel",
        "email": "tomasz.wrobel@nokia.com",
        "username": "twrobel"
      },
      "updated": "2020-11-18 08:15:18.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "8065dfd5_73af72a5",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0cc20694_d458297d",
      "file_path": "certServiceClient/src/main/java/org/onap/oom/certservice/client/configuration/validation/UriValidator.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 27,
      "message": "Still, it would look like more \"reliable\" if there would be a comment that this monster regex is based on some smaller regex from official document. Without any comment its hard to understand and to trust that it works ;)\n\nUnless it's invented from scratch of found on stackoverflow 😄\n\nAnyway any sort of commend would be helpful for further developers.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6714,
        "name": "Jan Malkiewicz",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jan.malkiewicz@nokia.com",
        "username": "jmalkiewicz"
      },
      "updated": "2020-11-18 08:31:49.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "fa4a81d0_2a559621",
      "unresolved": true
    },
